The coexistence of CDs with H2O2, HRP and their mixture was tested. Interestingly, the fluorescence of the CDs enhanced significantly in the presence of H2O2 and HRP, accompanied by a small red-shift emission (Fig. 4

                        a, 4b and 
                           Figure S3
                        ). Meanwhile, the fluorescence intensities of the CDs were almost unchanged or increased slightly with the addition of individual H2O2 or HRP·H2O2, HRP or their mixture solution are non-fluorescent (
                           Figure S4
                        ). The results provided a feasible way to construct a “turn-on” sensor for H2O2 detection.

The effects of some key experimental parameters on H2O2 determination were investigated, including pH value, HRP concentration, reaction time and temperature (Supporting information, Figure S6 ). The enhancement degree of the CDs (ΔF = F – F0) was used to evaluate the performance, where F0 and F represent the fluorescence intensities of the solutions in the absence and presence of H2O2. In detail, F0 was obtained by the binary mixture of CDs and HRP; F was obtained by the ternary mixture of CDs, HRP and H2O2. The fluorescence enhancement values of the CDs increased clearly with pH values increasing from 3.0 to 7.0, changed slightly from pH = 7.0 to 8.0 and then decreased obviously with pH > 8.0 (Fig. S6 a). In the literature, the optimal pH for HRP is about 7.0 and HRP activity decreased clearly in strong acid and alkaline conditions [33]. The effect of pH on sensing system is probably attributed to the changes of HRP activity. In addition, pH value could affect the protonation degree of surface functional groups of the CDs as well as the “aggregation” of the CDs. Therefore, the optimal pH value of the sensing system was set at 7.4 with the highest ΔF. In addition, blue-shift emission of the mixture solution with pH increasing was observed, similar to that of CDs. With the increase of HRP concentration from 0 to 80 μg/mL, the fluorescence enhancement degree of the solution (ΔF) was clearly increased and changed slightly with further addition of HRP (Fig. S6 b). HRP alone could also cause a slight increase of the CDs fluorescence, and the fluorescence intensity (F0) increased slowly and then changed slightly with increasing HRP concentration (
Figure S7
). By contrast, in the presence of H2O2, the fluorescence intensity of the ternary mixture (F) increased largely with increasing HRP concentration and then almost unchanged (
Figure S7
). Thus, 100 μg/mL of HRP was used in the following experiments. The reaction time was optimized and 40 min was selected for H2O2 detection (Fig. S6 c). The effect of the incubation temperature was investigated and the experiments were performed at room temperature (25 ℃) to be convenient (Fig. S6 d). At the optimal conditions, a series of H2O2 solutions ranging from 0 to 100 μM were analyzed. With increasing H2O2 concentration, the fluorescence at 526 nm increased gradually and then changed slightly (Fig. 5
a and 5b). The calibration curve was constructed by plotting the fluorescence enhancement degree (ΔF) versus H2O2 concentration in the range of 0.1 to 8 μM. The obtained regression equation was Y = 138.54CH2O2 + 42.68 with a linear coefficient of 0.9978 (inset of Fig. 5 b).

The effect of some potential interferents was investigated, including metal ions, biomolecules and saccharides. In Fig. 6, most of the interferents had a slight effect on the fluorescence of the CDs. The addition of Fe2+ and Fe3+ could cause a certain increase in the fluorescence of the CDs, probably attributed to the increased HRP activity. The addition of AA could cause an obvious fluorescence decrease of the system, probably due to the reduce ability of AA resulted in suppressing the oxidation of carbon dots. Meanwhile, glucose addition could lead to a remarkable fluorescence enhancement. The effect of the coexistence of ferric ions or AA with glucose were further investigated. Normal levels of ferric ions and AA in human serum were lower than 30 and 100 μM, respectively [36,37]. The low concentration of ferric ions and AA had a slight effect on glucose determination (Supporting information, 
                           Figure S9
                        ). The results indicates this sensing system is highly selective to glucose detection, which is similar to other turn-on methods owing to the intrinsic merit of turn-on strategy [15–17,22,34]. This method is feasible to detect glucose in real biological samples and could be useful for screening trace targets mediated by H2O2 generation.
